eason is not to do with race, but just because they live in a rural area where the local first-level schools are in their view bad...and the nearest good schools in the city would be a huge, expensive commute. Both work from home (they have a small business), both have teaching qualifications, and I'm willing to teach the kid basic English...so it sounds fine... &#10;But the problem is that the kid will be all by herself (they are hoping to provide her with siblings, but this takes time...)., so they've decided only to go ahead if they can find at least one or two kids of similar age whose parents would be interested, or somehow work out a programme of extra activities in the area where the kid can make local friends and get social and independent experience.... &#10;Even if all the other conditions are there - this social experience aspect is really key. And learning alone - or with a sibling at a rather different stage in learning - also lacks those two key reciprocal elements - the competitive and the co-operative. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1329" language="en" documentId="779" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="sarka" date="07 January 2011 12:16pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/9050893" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="3" thumbsDown="0" origId="779" notes="" title="Why I home school my children"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="189"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="190" end="668"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="669" end="1072"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="1073" end="1329"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>